History &\nMechanism Imaging\nclinical\nof injury strategy\nsuspicion\nCommon Emergency presentations\nFractures\n▪ A fracture is a complete\ndisruption in the continuity of\nthe bone.\n▪ If only some of the trabeculae\nare severes while other is intact\nor just bent the fracture is\nincomplete an example of this\nis green stick fracture.\n▪ X-ray is first line imaging\nmodality\n▪ CT & MRI complementary\nroles.\nApproach to describe a fracture\n1. Projections and clinical history What radiograph (or radiographs) are you looking\nat\n2. Fracture type When describing a fracture, the first thing to mention is what type of\nfracture it is. Broadly, these can be split into\n1. Complete\n2. Incomplete\n3. Salter Harris\nComplete: all the way through the bone\n▪ Transverse: straight across the bone\n▪ Oblique: an oblique line across the bone\n▪ Spiral: looks like a corkscrew\n▪ Comminuted: more than 2 parts to the fracture\n12"}